{"title_page": "Jacob Kroger", "text_new": "{{short description|German goldsmith and thief}}\n[[File:Adrian Vanson Anne of Denmark 1595.jpg|thumb|right|Jacob Kroger made and repaired jewels for [[Anne of Denmark]] then stole them.]]\n'''Jacob Kroger''' (d. 1594), was a German goldsmith who worked for [[Anne of Denmark]] in Scotland and stole her jewels.\n\nKroger was a citizen of the [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg]], ruled by Anne of Denmark's brother-in-law, [[Henry Julius, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg]].<ref>[[Mary Anne Everett Green]], [https://archive.org/details/calendarofstatep05grea/page/364 ''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), pp. 364-5].</ref> He completed his apprenticeship as a goldsmith at [[L\u00fcneburg]] in 1575 instructed by the master goldsmiths T\u00f6nnies Dierssen or Dirksen and Steffen Ulrichs or Olrikes.<ref>Wolfgang Scheffler, ''Goldschmiede Niedersachsen'', vol. 1 (Berlin, 1965), p. 907.</ref> Dierssen, whose hallmark was an antelope, made objects such as highly decorative spoons,<ref>[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/188321 'Figure-top spoon, ca. 1560\u201390. Probably by T\u00f6nnies Dierssen.' The Metropolitan Museum of Art, 97.2.298].</ref> and cups.<ref>[https://www.deutsche-digitale-bibliothek.de/item/5245HSWMIKP6D5WBTRL7DOATC6OO33X3 Jagdpokal aus dem L\u00fcneburger Ratssilber, Kunstgewerbemuseum, Staatliche Museen zu Berlin, 1874,382].</ref> Kroger's L\u00fcneburg contemporaries Luleff Meier and Dirich Utermarke made a mirror frame decorated with theme of [[Nebuchadnezzar II|Nebuchadnezzar]] from the [[Book of Daniel]].<ref>[https://skd-online-collection.skd.museum/Details/Index/117266 'L\u00fcneburger Spiegel in epitaphf\u00f6rmigem Prunkrahmen', Green Vault, Dresden Gr\u00fcnes Gew\u00f6lbe, IV 110].</ref>\n[[File:Jagdpokal - Bekr\u00f6nung - Krieger frontal.jpg|thumb|left|Figure for the cover of a cup by T\u00f6nnies Dierssen, one of Jacob Kroger's teachers, [[Kunstgewerbemuseum Berlin]]]]\nJacob Kroger came to Scotland with [[Anne of Denmark]] and her husband [[James VI of Scotland]] in 1590. He was a member of her household and was accommodated with her at [[Holyroodhouse]] or [[Dunfermline Palace]], where he would eat his meals at the head of a table with other Danish servants, including her tailors, the keeper of her furs, her cellar man and carpenter. These were lower status servants, who dined in a separate room from the queen at \"the second table for the Danes in her Grace's [[Henry Lindsay, 13th Earl of Crawford|Master Household's]] Hall.\"<ref>''Papers Relative to the Marriage of King James the Sixth of Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1828), p. 37, see also [[National Library of Scotland]] Adv. MS 34.2.17.</ref>\n\n[[John Carey, 3rd Baron Hunsdon|John Carey]], an English official at [[Berwick upon Tweed]] met Kroger, and wrote, \"This Dane was the queen's jeweller and made most of her jewels himself and had the keeping of most of them.\"<ref>''Border Papers'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1894), p. 538 (modernised here).</ref>\n\n==Jewel thieves==\nIn April 1594 Kroger and a French servant, Guillaume Martyn, a footman who worked in the king's stables (and had taken care of the king's camel), decided to steal some of the queen's jewels and return to their home countries via England, because they had not been paid. After petitioning the king and queen for money with no results they were \"very weary of their service\". They left at Edinburgh at night and crossed the [[River Tweed|Tweed]] near [[Kelso, Scottish Borders|Kelso]]. They were seen on the road between [[Belford, Northumberland|Belford]] and [[Alnwick]] by Captain Carvell, a soldier at [[Bewcastle Castle|Bewcastle]], and came to [[Tweedmouth]]. According to John Carey, instead of making further progress, they remained near [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] for a few days. Carey could easily have taken them, but no word of their crime was heard from Edinburgh for three days.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/cu31924091786057/page/n589 ''Border Papers'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1894), pp. 538-9].</ref> On 3 May [[John Colville (c. 1540\u20131605)|John Colville]] wrote to the poet [[Henry Lok]] in London with news of the theft for [[Robert Cecil, 1st Earl of Salisbury|Sir Robert Cecil]].<ref>[https://archive.org/details/calendarofmanusc04grea/page/522 ''Calendar of the manuscripts of the Most Honourable the Marquess of Salisbury preserved at Hatfield House'', vol. 4 (London, 1892), p. 524].</ref>\n\n==Capture==\nOn 6 May 1594 they met the [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell|Earl of Bothwell]], who was a fugitive in the north of England, at [[Seaton Delaval Hall|Edward Delaval's house]] at [[North Shields]] and he took all, or nearly all, their possessions. Then [[George Selby]], Sheriff of [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], and Thomas Power, a servant of the [[Henry Percy, 9th Earl of Northumberland|Earl of Northumberland]] and Lieutenant of [[Tynemouth Castle]], arrested them, following requests froms James VI.<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 339, 342-3, 356-7.</ref> Power had to pay a fee of 5 shillings to the [[Bailiff]] of North Shields to make the arrest. The Bailiff had prevented Bothwell taking Kroger and Martyn back to Scotland and had summoned Power and Selby.<ref>Richard Welford, ''History of Newcastle and Gateshead'', vol. 3 (London, 1887), p. 90.</ref> The prisoners were taken to Tynemouth Castle.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/s3proceedings10sociuoft/page/284 'Tynemouth', ''Proceedings of the Society of Antiquaries of Newcastle'', vol. 10 no. 24 (1902), p. 285]: [https://archive.org/details/reportofroyalcom06grea/page/232 ''HMC 6th Report (Northumberland)'' (London, 1877), p. 232] giving Guillaume's surname as \"Bl...\", and calling Kroger \"Jeanes Krogar\".</ref> The Mayor of Newcastle, Lionel Maddison, wrote to Robert Cecil with news of the arrest.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), p. 365].</ref>\n[[File:Prieur\u00e9 Ch\u00e2teau Tynemouth North Tyneside 17.jpg|thumb|right|Jacob Kroger and his partner Guillaume Martyn spent a month in [[Tynemouth Castle]] before their rendition.]]\nPower described some of the jewels in a letter to the [[Henry Percy, 9th Earl of Northumberland|Earl of Northumberland]] as goldsmith's work, neckchains, and bracelets of ragged pearl. He enclosed an inventory of the jewels, with values provided by \"James Krugar of Lunburg\" and signed \"Jachob Kroger\", which includes; a chain of pearls to go twice about her neck worth 60 crowns, a black stone heart set in gold with a pendant pearl worth 2 crowns, two double pearl rings for a gown worth 60 crowns, and gold shells of two sizes and aiglettes for the body of the queen's gowns worth 600 crowns.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/historyofnewcast03welf/page/90 Richard Welford, ''History of Newcastle and Gateshead'', vol. 3 (London, 1887), p. 90]: ''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), pp. 364-5, TNA SP15/33/30-32.</ref>\n\nThere was a conflict of authority and jurisdictions in Northumberland over the fugitives. Several English landowners were friends to Bothwell and welcomed him in their houses, despite a proclamation forbidding this. The Bailiff of Shields had taken control of the situation at Edward Delaval's house, and allowed the Earl of Northumberland's men to arrest Kroger and Martyn. [[John Forster (soldier)|Sir John Forster]], warden of the Middle March, asked Lionel Maddison, the Mayor of Newcastle, about the arrest and the whereabouts of the prisoners and he denied all knowledge.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), p. 366.</ref>\n\n[[Robert Bowes (diplomat)|Robert Bowes]], an English diplomat in Edinburgh, wrote on 9 June to [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley|William Cecil]] that Bothwell had taken some of the jewels, and wanted to use them to make his peace, to effect his reconciliation, with James VI. James wanted the prisoners sent to John Carey at [[Berwick upon Tweed]] and delivered to his representative, John Hume of [[Hutton Castle|Hutton Hall]]. James VI described the thieves as \"twa limers deuces\".<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 342-3, 356-7.</ref> Thomas Power brought the prisoners to John Carey at Berwick.<ref>''Border Papers'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1894), p. 538.</ref> Carey sent another version of the inventory of the jewels to Robert Cecil, with a receipt from Thomas Power for a bag of red buckram tied with white tape containing the gold studs and aiglettes, two wings of a gown sewn with pearls, the nether skirt of an old black satin gown, a pair of blue taffeta sleeves, white taffeta from the lining of a garment, and two pieces of carnation coloured satin. According to Krogar and Martyn, Bothwell had kept the other jewels including rings, bracelets, and the black heart. Krogar signed this statement \"Jachob Kroger Van Lunebarge\". The valuations were attributed, presumably in error, to \"Francys Crugar\".<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), p. 368: TNA SP15/33/46.</ref>\n\n[[Mary, Queen of Scots]] had owned velvet gowns embroidered with pearls, but an inventory of Anne of Denmark's clothes made in 1608 only mentions three items with seed pearls and none with aglets, and such adornments may have gone out of fashion.<ref>Joseph Robertson, ''Inventaires de la Royne Descosse'' (Edinburgh, 1863), p. 65: Jemma Field, 'The Wardrobe Goods of Anna of Denmark', ''Costume'', 51:1 (2017), pp. 15-16.</ref> Thomas Power mentioned \"ragged pearls\", which were used to embroider [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth's]] gowns and were used in 1602 to refurbish an old gown given to [[Frances Howard, Countess of Kildare|Lady Kildare]]. There was a stock of ragged pearls, regarded as of small value, in Anne of Denmark's wardrobe in 1619.<ref>Janet Arnold, ''Queen Elizabeth's Wardrobe Unlock'd'' (Leeds, 1988), pp. 175, 255, 263, 272, 278.</ref>\n\n[[John Selby (died 1595)|Sir John Selby]] of [[Twizell Castle|Twizell]], English depute [[Lord Warden of the Marches|warden of the East March]], delivered Kroger, Martyn, and the jewels to John Hume of Hutton Hall, the Scottish depute warden of the East March, on 11 June 1594, a day of truce, at the west ford of [[Norham]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), p. 368.</ref> Hume gave Selby a receipt for both men and jewels with another inventory, which mentions the silk threading attached to the aiglettes and studs in the red bag.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), p. 368: TNA SP15/33/48.</ref>\n\nThe two fugitives were returned to Edinburgh and they were executed by hanging three days later on Friday 14 June 1594 after a brief trial.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), p. 369.</ref>\n\nThe queen's next goldsmith was a French man, called \"Clei\", succeeded on 27 July 1597 by [[George Heriot]].<ref>''Memoirs of George Heriot'' (Edinburgh, 1822), p. 12 quoting [https://archive.org/details/fragmentsscotis00dalygoog/page/n150 'Diarey of Robert Birrel' (Edinburgh, 1798), p. 48].</ref>  Ten years later, jewels were allegedly stolen from Anne of Denmark by [[Margaret Hartsyde]], and after her death in 1619 by her Danish servant Anna and a French page Piero Hugon.<ref>Maureen M. Meikle & Helen M. Payne, 'From Lutheranism to Catholicism: The Faith of Anna of Denmark (1574-1619)', ''Journal of Ecclesiastical History'', 64:1 (2013), pp. 66-9.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kroger, Jeanes}}\n[[Category:1594 deaths]]\n[[Category:German goldsmiths]]\n[[Category:People from L\u00fcneburg]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:Household of Anne of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Jewel thieves]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German goldsmith and thief}}\n[[File:Adrian Vanson Anne of Denmark 1595.jpg|thumb|right|Jacob Kroger made and repaired jewels for [[Anne of Denmark]] then stole them.]]\n'''Jacob Kroger''' (d. 1594), was a German goldsmith who worked for [[Anne of Denmark]] in Scotland and stole her jewels.\n\nKroger was a citizen of the [[Principality of L\u00fcneburg]], ruled by Anne of Denmark's brother-in-law, [[Henry Julius, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg]].<ref>[[Mary Anne Everett Green]], [https://archive.org/details/calendarofstatep05grea/page/364 ''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), pp. 364-5].</ref> He completed his apprenticeship as a goldsmith at [[L\u00fcneburg]] in 1575 instructed by the master goldsmiths T\u00f6nnies Dierssen or Dirksen and Steffen Ulrichs or Olrikes.<ref>Wolfgang Scheffler, ''Goldschmiede Niedersachsen'', vol. 1 (Berlin, 1965), p. 907.</ref> Dierssen, whose hallmark was an antelope, made objects such as highly decorative spoons,<ref>[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/188321 'Figure-top spoon, ca. 1560\u201390. Probably by T\u00f6nnies Dierssen.' The Metropolitan Museum of Art, 97.2.298].</ref> and cups.<ref>[https://www.deutsche-digitale-bibliothek.de/item/5245HSWMIKP6D5WBTRL7DOATC6OO33X3 Jagdpokal aus dem L\u00fcneburger Ratssilber, Kunstgewerbemuseum, Staatliche Museen zu Berlin, 1874,382].</ref> Kroger's L\u00fcneburg contemporaries Luleff Meier and Dirich Utermarke made a mirror frame decorated with theme of [[Nebuchadnezzar II|Nebuchadnezzar]] from the [[Book of Daniel]].<ref>[https://skd-online-collection.skd.museum/Details/Index/117266 'L\u00fcneburger Spiegel in epitaphf\u00f6rmigem Prunkrahmen', Green Vault, Dresden Gr\u00fcnes Gew\u00f6lbe, IV 110].</ref>\n[[File:Jagdpokal - Bekr\u00f6nung - Krieger frontal.jpg|thumb|left|Figure for the cover of a cup by T\u00f6nnies Dierssen, one of Jacob Kroger's teachers, [[Kunstgewerbemuseum Berlin]]]]\nJacob Kroger came to Scotland with [[Anne of Denmark]] and her husband [[James VI of Scotland]] in 1590. He was a member of her household and was accommodated with her at [[Holyroodhouse]] or [[Dunfermline Palace]], where he would eat his meals at the head of a table with other Danish servants, including her tailors, the keeper of her furs, her cellar man and carpenter. These were lower status servants, who dined in a separate room from the queen at \"the second table for the Danes in her Grace's [[Henry Lindsay, 13th Earl of Crawford|Master Household's]] Hall.\"<ref>''Papers Relative to the Marriage of King James the Sixth of Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1828), p. 37, see also [[National Library of Scotland]] Adv. MS 34.2.17.</ref>\n\n[[John Carey, 3rd Baron Hunsdon|John Carey]], an English official at [[Berwick upon Tweed]] met Kroger, and wrote, \"This Dane was the queen's jeweller and made most of her jewels himself and had the keeping of most of them.\"<ref>''Border Papers'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1894), p. 538 (modernised here).</ref>\n\n==Jewel thieves==\nIn April 1594 Kroger and a French servant, Guillaume Martyn, a footman who worked in the king's stables (and had taken care of the king's camel), decided to steal some of the queen's jewels and return to their home countries via England, because they had not been paid. After petitioning the king and queen for money with no results they were \"very weary of their service\". They left at Edinburgh at night and crossed the [[River Tweed|Tweed]] near [[Kelso, Scottish Borders|Kelso]]. They were seen on the road between [[Belford, Northumberland|Belford]] and [[Alnwick]] by Captain Carvell, a soldier at [[Bewcastle Castle|Bewcastle]], and came to [[Tweedmouth]]. According to John Carey, instead of making further progress, they remained near [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] for a few days. Carey could easily have taken them, but no word of their crime was heard from Edinburgh for three days.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/cu31924091786057/page/n589 ''Border Papers'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1894), pp. 538-9].</ref> On 3 May [[John Colville (c. 1540\u20131605)|John Colville]] wrote to the poet [[Henry Lok]] in London with news of the theft for [[Robert Cecil, 1st Earl of Salisbury|Sir Robert Cecil]].<ref>[https://archive.org/details/calendarofmanusc04grea/page/522 ''Calendar of the manuscripts of the Most Honourable the Marquess of Salisbury preserved at Hatfield House'', vol. 4 (London, 1892), p. 524].</ref>\n\n==Capture==\nOn 6 May 1594 they met the [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell|Earl of Bothwell]], who was a fugitive in the north of England, at [[Seaton Delaval Hall|Edward Delaval's house]] at [[North Shields]] and he took all, or nearly all, their possessions. Then [[George Selby]], Sheriff of [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], and Thomas Power, a servant of the [[Henry Percy, 9th Earl of Northumberland|Earl of Northumberland]] and Lieutenant of [[Tynemouth Castle]], arrested them, following requests froms James VI.<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 339, 342-3, 356-7.</ref> Power had to pay a fee of 5 shillings to the [[Bailiff]] of North Shields to make the arrest. The Bailiff had prevented Bothwell taking Kroger and Martyn back to Scotland and had summoned Power and Selby.<ref>Richard Welford, ''History of Newcastle and Gateshead'', vol. 3 (London, 1887), p. 90.</ref> The prisoners were taken to Tynemouth Castle.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/s3proceedings10sociuoft/page/284 'Tynemouth', ''Proceedings of the Society of Antiquaries of Newcastle'', vol. 10 no. 24 (1902), p. 285]: [https://archive.org/details/reportofroyalcom06grea/page/232 ''HMC 6th Report (Northumberland)'' (London, 1877), p. 232] giving Guillaume's surname as \"Bl...\", and calling Kroger \"Jeanes Krogar\".</ref> The Mayor of Newcastle, Lionel Maddison, wrote to Robert Cecil with news of the arrest.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), p. 365].</ref>\n[[File:Prieur\u00e9 Ch\u00e2teau Tynemouth North Tyneside 17.jpg|thumb|right|Jacob Kroger and his partner Guillaume Martyn spent a month in [[Tynemouth Castle]] before their rendition.]]\nPower described some of the jewels in a letter to the [[Henry Percy, 9th Earl of Northumberland|Earl of Northumberland]] as goldsmith's work, neckchains, and bracelets of ragged pearl. He enclosed an inventory of the jewels, with values provided by \"James Krugar of Lunburg\" and signed \"Jachob Kroger\", which includes; a chain of pearls to go twice about her neck worth 60 crowns, a black stone heart set in gold with a pendant pearl worth 2 crowns, two double pearl rings for a gown worth 60 crowns, and gold shells of two sizes and aiglettes for the body of the queen's gowns worth 600 crowns.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/historyofnewcast03welf/page/90 Richard Welford, ''History of Newcastle and Gateshead'', vol. 3 (London, 1887), p. 90]: ''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), pp. 364-5, TNA SP15/33/30-32.</ref>\n\nThere was a conflict of authority and jurisdictions in Northumberland over the fugitives. Several English landowners were friends to Bothwell and welcomed him in their houses, despite a proclamation forbidding this. The Bailiff of Shields had taken control of the situation at Edward Delaval's house, and allowed the Earl of Northumberland's men to arrest Kroger and Martyn. [[John Forster (soldier)|Sir John Forster]], warden of the Middle March, asked Lionel Maddison, the Mayor of Newcastle, about the arrest and the whereabouts of the prisoners and he denied all knowledge.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), p. 366.</ref>\n\n[[Robert Bowes (diplomat)|Robert Bowes]], an English diplomat in Edinburgh, wrote on 9 June to [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley|William Cecil]] that Bothwell had taken some of the jewels, and wanted to use them to make his peace, to effect his reconciliation, with James VI. James wanted the prisoners sent to John Carey at [[Berwick upon Tweed]] and delivered to his representative, John Hume of [[Hutton Castle|Hutton Hall]]. James VI described the thieves as \"twa limers deuces\".<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 342-3, 356-7.</ref> Thomas Power brought the prisoners to John Carey at Berwick.<ref>''Border Papers'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1894), p. 538.</ref> Carey sent another version of the inventory of the jewels to Robert Cecil, with a receipt from Thomas Power for a bag of red buckram tied with white tape containing the gold studs and aiglettes, two wings of a gown sewn with pearls, the nether skirt of an old black satin gown, a pair of blue taffeta sleeves, white taffeta from the lining of a garment, and two pieces of carnation coloured satin. According to Krogar and Martyn, Bothwell had kept the other jewels including rings, bracelets, and the black heart. Krogar signed this statement \"Jachob Kroger Van Lunebarge\". The valuations were attributed, presumably in error, to \"Francys Crugar\".<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), p. 368: TNA SP15/33/46.</ref>\n\n[[Mary, Queen of Scots]] had owned velvet gowns embroidered with pearls, but an inventory of Anne of Denmark's clothes made in 1608 only mentions three items with seed pearls and none with aglets, and such adornments may have gone out of fashion.<ref>Joseph Robertson, ''Inventaires de la Royne Descosse'' (Edinburgh, 1863), p. 65: Jemma Field, 'The Wardrobe Goods of Anna of Denmark', ''Costume'', 51:1 (2017), pp. 15-16.</ref> Thomas Power mentioned \"ragged pearls\", which were used to embroider [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth's]] gowns and were used in 1602 to refurbish an old gown given to [[Frances Howard, Countess of Kildare|Lady Kildare]]. There was a stock of ragged pearls, regarded as of small value, in Anne of Denmark's wardrobe in 1619.<ref>Janet Arnold, ''Queen Elizabeth's Wardrobe Unlock'd'' (Leeds, 1988), pp. 175, 255, 263, 272, 278.</ref>\n\n[[John Selby (died 1595)|Sir John Selby]] of [[Twizell Castle|Twizell]], English depute [[Lord Warden of the Marches|warden of the East March]], delivered Kroger, Martyn, and the jewels to John Hume of Hutton Hall, the Scottish depute warden of the East March, on 11 June 1594, a day of truce, at the west ford of [[Norham]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), p. 368.</ref> Hume gave Selby a receipt for both men and jewels with another inventory, which mentions the silk threading attached to the aiglettes and studs in the red bag.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), p. 368: TNA SP15/33/48.</ref>\n\nThe two fugitives were returned to Edinburgh and they were executed by hanging three days later on Friday 14 June 1594 after a brief trial.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, Addenda 1580-1625'' (London, 1872), p. 369.</ref>\n\nThe queen's next goldsmith was a French man, called \"Clei\", succeeded on 27 July 1597 by [[George Heriot]].<ref>''Memoirs of George Heriot'' (Edinburgh, 1822), p. 12 quoting [https://archive.org/details/fragmentsscotis00dalygoog/page/n150 'Diarey of Robert Birrel' (Edinburgh, 1798), p. 48].</ref>  Ten years later, jewels were allegedly stolen from Anne of Denmark by [[Margaret Hartsyde]], and after her death in 1619 by her Danish servant Anna and a French page Piero Hugon.<ref>Maureen M. Meikle & Helen M. Payne, 'From Lutheranism to Catholicism: The Faith of Anna of Denmark (1574-1619)', ''Journal of Ecclesiastical History'', 64:1 (2013), pp. 66-9.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kroger, Jeanes}}\n[[Category:1594 deaths]]\n[[Category:German goldsmiths]]\n[[Category:People from L\u00fcneburg]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:Jewel thieves]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "cat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacob_Kroger"}
